{
  "slug": "mel-at-100-the-mel-brooks-movie-rankings-plus-scary-movie-is",
  "title": "Mel at 100: The Mel Brooks Movie Rankings. Plus: ‘Scary Movie’ Is Terrifyingly Awful",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2026-06-09",
  "runtimeMin": 112,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda open on a fifth straight boom weekend at the box office and a 'Scary Movie' reboot no one in the theater was laughing at, then Yasi Salek and Adam Nayman join to mark Mel Brooks's 100th birthday by ranking all 11 films he directed.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The box office boom",
      "note": "five straight weekends of ‘we're back’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Obsession",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Curry Barker's word-of-mouth hit keeps climbing week over week. One industry figure Sean spoke to compared it to Easy Rider. It's on track to outgross Backrooms despite a fraction of the opening."
        },
        {
          "title": "Backrooms",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "Kane Parsons's $80 million opening rode a built-in fan base, but the general public is cooling on it faster than on Obsession."
        },
        {
          "title": "Masters of the Universe",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "The He-Man movie made about $30 million, not a disaster on its own but a bomb against its IP and budget."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Scary Movie’",
      "note": "the reboot at the top of the box office",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Scary Movie",
          "year": 2026,
          "note": "A $55 million opening for supposedly dead IP, reuniting most of the original cast: Wayans brothers, Anna Faris, Regina Hall. Both hosts found it painfully unfunny and their audiences barely laughed, but the marketing works: a trailer stacked with references (Sinners, Smile, M3GAN, Longlegs) is enough. Sean's one defense is the livestream scene. The old satirists are now the veterans taking shots at younger filmmakers' work."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "ranking",
      "heading": "The Mel Brooks Movie Rankings",
      "note": "with Yasi Salek and Adam Nayman, on Brooks's 100th birthday · all 11 he directed",
      "subject": "Mel Brooks",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Young Frankenstein",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "No. 1. The consensus best-made of the 11: camera, lenses, sets, Peter Boyle's monster. Sean and Adam's pick; Amanda grants it's the finest achievement even if Blazing Saddles is her favorite."
        },
        {
          "title": "Blazing Saddles",
          "year": 1974,
          "note": "No. 2. The most important one, and the one older listeners name first. Richard Pryor in the writers' room, Madeline Kahn's Dietrich number; still bracing enough that Adam wants to screen it just to see what a room does with it."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Producers",
          "year": 1967,
          "note": "No. 3. The Oscar-winning script and his one fully original idea. More polished than anyone remembered; Springtime for Hitler lands harder for arriving 20 years after the war."
        },
        {
          "title": "Spaceballs",
          "year": 1987,
          "note": "No. 4. The most beloved, made because his kids wore out the Star Wars tapes. Bill Pullman doing Harrison Ford, Rick Moranis's Dark Helmet; Sean finds it over-reliant on its source."
        },
        {
          "title": "History of the World, Part I",
          "year": 1981,
          "note": "No. 5. The anthology format saves it: a weak sketch is only ten minutes from a good one. The Spanish Inquisition musical and the Viking funeral are the keepers."
        },
        {
          "title": "Robin Hood: Men in Tights",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "No. 6, on sentiment. Cary Elwes spoofing his own Princess Bride shtick, Dave Chappelle at 19; the contemporary gags have a short shelf life."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Twelve Chairs",
          "year": 1970,
          "note": "No. 7. The forgotten one, a 1928 Russian novel turned Bolshevik buddy comedy. Frank Langella pre-Dracula; Yasi's soft spot, and the ending got her."
        },
        {
          "title": "High Anxiety",
          "year": 1977,
          "note": "No. 8. The Hitchcock homage, too reverent and too close to work: Hitch was already funny. Best when Brooks drops the parody and just sings the title song."
        },
        {
          "title": "Silent Movie",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "No. 9. A blank-check tribute to silent cinema that cuts him off from his best tool, his voice. The Marcel Marceau gag is the highlight and the indictment."
        },
        {
          "title": "Life Stinks",
          "year": 1991,
          "note": "No. 10. The outlier: a sincere rich-man-goes-broke story, not a parody. Yasi defends it as a masterpiece; the others won't push it past 10."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dracula: Dead and Loving It",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "No. 11, dead last, unanimous. Cheaply made, and Leslie Nielsen's magic didn't survive the trip from the ZAZ team to Brooks."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
